      },
      "date": "2013-01-24 10:39:43.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Fails\n\nTests received by maloo, run on CentOS release 6.3/x86_64: (https://maloo.whamcloud.com/test_sessions/03924b98-660f-11e2-a42b-52540035b04c).  Ran 12 tests.  1 tests failed: sanity-quota.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "7388d9a0996e0d795939924f5500acbb97662e71",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2013-01-24 19:04:22.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't submit this\n\nListing all of the Lustre modules is brittle in the face of changes between versions. It would seem better to use something like lustre_rmmod to dynamically generate the list of modules based on the dependency reported by lsmod.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "2f4cb2055fd703872e23e8ccdf7ae2fc7a014914",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 124,
        "name": "Prakash Surya",
        "email": "lists@prakashsurya.com",
        "username": "prakash"
      },
      "date": "2013-01-24 19:22:57.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nInteresting, I wasn't even aware of that script. I agree, using the dependency tree dynamically is a much better way to go about this. I'll look into that.\n\nWith that said, I still think this should land. Until a better method is in place, the lnet script is bugged and this fixes the current problem. A \"correct\" fix can always land later.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "98d25418ee6b0d1ff7f9853ad0ce1b0912920d2b",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2013-01-25 08:48:58.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nPrakash,\nthe drawback of landing an \"ok\" fix instead of a \"good\" fix is that once the \"ok\" fix is landed there is little demand to develop and land the \"good\" fix later, but the problem remains in the code and will continue to break and need repair by a series of \"ok\" fixes each time.\n\nIdeally, rather than copying unload_dep_module() from lustre_rmmod into the \"lnet\" script, it would be better to enhance lustre_rmmod to add an argument to remove the \"upper\" modules first, and then stop lnet, and then remove the remaining modules, something like:\n\n lustre_rmmod -a lnet  # remove only modules above lnet\n stop_lnet\n lustre_rmmod\n\nThat avoids duplication of code, and ensures that if lustre_rmmod is improved that it will also propagate to the lnet script automatically.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "6a7fc5a3c3726e557178257469b9787b473b63ea",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 124,
        "name": "Prakash Surya",
        "email": "lists@prakashsurya.com",
        "username": "prakash"
      },
      "date": "2013-01-28 15:15:01.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't submit this\n\nFair enough. I'll make a proper fix to do that.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "59105133461ca67cab0d131cc749c95b08fb482a",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 109,
        "name": "Christopher J. Morrone",
        "email": "morrone2@llnl.gov",
        "username": "morrone"
      },
      "date": "2013-01-29 18:22:08.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nAt least in the past, part of the problem used to be that lsmod did not list all dependant modules.  Perhaps we've fixed that these days...",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
